NYPD Crime Statistics(2014-2015)¶

Dataset sourced from:https://www.kaggle.com/adamschroeder/crimes-new-york-city

In this dataset, each row represents a crime which has been registered in the NYPD for the years 2014 and 2015. It has specific details of the crime such as time and date of occurence, type of offence, location etc. With this notebook, I aim to do some exploratory analysis on the data and see if some interesting patterns emerge. The data was mostly clean except for the date column which was extremely messy, having dates in different formats, some using '-' as separator, some using '/'. I used Excel and the built in pandas funcitonalities to fix this.

Please use the 'Show/Hide Code' button below to show the code behind the graphs.

#data.to_csv('nypd_datefixed.csv', index=False)

data = pd.read_csv('nypd_datefixed.csv', parse_dates=['CMPLNT_FR_DT'])
In [244]:
#Code to get the day of the week, hour, year and month in a separate column

data['CMPLNT_FR_DT'] = pd.to_datetime(data['CMPLNT_FR_DT'], errors='coerce')
data['Day'] = data['CMPLNT_FR_DT'].dt.day_name()
data['CMPLNT_FR_TM'] = pd.to_datetime(data['CMPLNT_FR_TM'], errors='coerce')
data['Hour'] = data['CMPLNT_FR_TM'].dt.hour
data['Year'] = data['CMPLNT_FR_DT'].dt.year
data['Month'] = data['CMPLNT_FR_DT'].dt.month
In [247]:
#Renaming some columns for ease of use

data.rename(columns={'BORO_NM':'Borough', 'OFNS_DESC':'Offence Type', 'LAW_CAT_CD':'Crime Class',
                     'PREM_TYP_DESC':'Location Type'}, inplace=True)

In [248]:
sns.set_style("darkgrid")
fig_dims = (18, 10)
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=fig_dims)
ax.set_xticklabels(ax.get_xticklabels(), rotation=40, ha="right")
ax.tick_params(labelsize=18)
ax.set_xlabel('Offence Type', fontsize=20)
ax.set_ylabel('Count', fontsize=20)
ax = sns.countplot(x='Offence Type', data=data, hue='Borough', palette='Set1', 
              order=data['Offence Type'].value_counts().iloc[:10].index)


plt.setp(ax.get_legend().get_texts(), fontsize='18')
plt.setp(ax.get_legend().get_title(), fontsize='18')
plt.show()

Observations:¶

1. Petit larceny is the most common crime, which according to wikipedia is defined as a crime involving the unlawful 
   taking or theft of the personal property of another person or business.

2. Highest number of crimes are reported from Brooklyn followed by Manhattan. This can possibly be due to Brooklyn 
   being the most populous of the 5 boroughs. But Queens is as populous as Brooklyn which leads me to believe that 
   socio-economic factors are at play here.  

3. Staten Island has the least crimes on account of it being the least populous of the boroughs.

#make pivot table with value counts as value

data['ones'] = 1
pivot_day_hour = data.pivot_table(values='ones', index='Day', columns='Hour', aggfunc='sum')
pivot_day_hour.index = pd.CategoricalIndex(pivot_day_hour.index, categories= ["Sunday", "Monday", "Tuesday", "Wednesday",
                                                                              "Thursday", "Friday", "Saturday"])
pivot_day_hour.sort_index(level=0, inplace=True)
In [251]:
fig_dims = (21, 10)
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=fig_dims)
ax.set_xlabel("Hour",fontsize=15)
ax.set_ylabel("Day",fontsize=15)
ax.tick_params(labelsize=15)

ax = sns.heatmap(pivot_day_hour,cmap='Reds',linecolor='white',linewidths=1)

Observations:¶

1. Predictably, crimes occur mostly after dark with higher numbers during weekend hours or drunken revelry hours ie 
    Friday, and Saturday evenings.

2. There is an anomaly at the 12 hour mark shwoing an unusual uptick in crime compared to its neighbouring hours.
    Could this be a result of improper data entry? Confusion between hours 00 and 12?

In [255]:
#discard values less than 1000, take transpose to make groph neat

for i in pivot_prem_hour.columns:
    if not any(pivot_prem_hour[i] > 1000):
        pivot_prem_hour.drop(i,axis=1,inplace=True)
        
pivot_prem_hour = pivot_prem_hour.transpose()

Observations:¶

1. The patterns that emerge correspond to the regular movement of people. Bars and nightclubs has most cases 
    around midnight and early hours, shops during evening hours, commercial buildings and schools during regular 
    office hours.
3. Residences have the most crimes folowed by the streets.    
2. Patterns from houses reflect normal sleep patterns. Also noteworthy is apartments have more crimes than houses, due 
    to NYC having significantly more people living in apartments than houses
